===Etymology===
English from the 14th century, from Middle Latin {{term|biblia||book|lang=la}} (reinterpreted as a feminine from earlier Latin neuter plural {{term|biblia||books|lang=la}}), from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|βιβλία||books|tr=biblia|lang=grc}}, plural of {{term|βιβλίον||small book|tr=biblion|lang=grc}}, originally a diminutive of {{term|βίβλος||book|tr=biblos|lang=grc}}, from {{term|βύβλος||papyrus|tr=bublos|lang=grc}} (from the ancient [[Phoenicia]]n city of ''[[Byblos]]'' which exported this writing material).

Old English used ''biblioðece'' (from [[βιβλιοθήκη]]) for "the Scriptures".

